# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-democratic-national-convention
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 2, 1828.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Just as in the 1824 election, President John Quincy Adams of the National Republican Party faced Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party, making the election the second rematch in presidential history.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties were new organizations, and this was the first presidential election their nominees contested.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the collapse of the Federalist Party, four members of the Democratic-Republican Party, including Jackson and Adams, had sought the presidency in the 1824 election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had won a plurality (but not majority) of both the electoral vote and popular vote in the 1824 election, but had lost the contingent election that was held in the House of Representatives.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the aftermath of the election, Jackson's supporters accused Adams and Henry Clay of having reached a "corrupt bargain" in which Clay helped Adams win the contingent election in return for the position of Secretary of State.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the 1824 election, Jackson's supporters immediately began plans for a campaign in 1828, and the Democratic-Republican Party fractured into the National Republican Party and the Democratic Party during Adams's presidency.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The 1828 campaign was marked by large amounts of "mudslinging", as both parties attacked the personal qualities of the opposing party's candidate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson dominated in the South and the West, aided in part by the passage of the Tariff of 1828.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] With the ongoing expansion of the right to vote to most white men, the election marked a dramatic expansion of the electorate, with 9.5% of Americans casting a vote for president, compared with 3.4% in 1824.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Several states transitioned to a popular vote for president, leaving South Carolina and Delaware as the only states in which the legislature chose presidential electors.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson decisively won the election, carrying 55.5% of the popular vote and 178 electoral votes, to Adams' 83.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the rise of Jacksonian Democracy and the transition from the First Party System to the Second Party System.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historians debate the significance of the election, with many arguing that it marked the beginning of modern American politics by removing key barriers to voter participation and establishing a stable two-party system.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson became the first president whose home state was neither Massachusetts nor Virginia, while Adams was the second to lose re-election, following his father John Adams.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, unsuccessful candidate and Speaker of the House at the time, despised Jackson, in part due to their fight for Western votes during the election, and he chose to support Adams, which led to Adams being elected president on the first ballot.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A few days after the election, Adams appointed Clay his Secretary of State, a position held by Adams and his three immediate predecessors prior to becoming president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson and his followers promptly accused Clay and Adams of striking a "corrupt bargain," and continued to lambaste the president until the 1828 election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In 1824, the national Democratic-Republican Party collapsed as national politics became increasingly polarized between supporters of Adams and supporters of Jackson.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In a prelude to the presidential election, the Jacksonians bolstered their numbers in Congress in the 1826 congressional elections, with Jackson ally Andrew Stevenson chosen as the new Speaker of the House of Representatives in 1827 over Adams ally Speaker, John W.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In October 1825, the Tennessee legislature re-nominated Jackson for president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional opponents of Adams, including former William H.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford supporter Martin Van Buren, rallied around Jackson's candidacy.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's supporters called themselves *Democrats*, and would formally organize as the Democratic Party shortly after his election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In hopes of uniting those opposed to Adams, Jackson ran on a ticket with Calhoun.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] No congressional nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' relationship with Vice President John C.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun deteriorated, with Calhoun opposing Clay's appointment as Secretary of State due to his own presidential ambitions.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In June 1826, Calhoun gave his support to Jackson for the 1828 election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun's stance on the removal of Native Americans was not accepted by the Georgian electors who instead voted for William Smith.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, who supported Crawford during the 1824 election, supported Jackson during the 1828 election and aided in the selection of Calhoun as vice president in order to prevent DeWitt Clinton, his political enemy, from being selected.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren arranged for incidents to divide Calhoun and Adams such as him abstaining from a vote on tariff legislation supported by Adams in order for Calhoun to break the tie by voting against it.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Ritchie, editor of the *Richmond Examiner*, was one of the leading supporters of Crawford during the 1824 election and Van Buren convinced him to support Jackson.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren convinced him of an alliance "between the planters of the South and the plain Republicans of the North".
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was re-nominated on the endorsement of state legislatures and partisan rallies.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] As with the Democrats, no nominating caucus or national convention was held.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams chose Secretary of the Treasury Richard Rush, a Pennsylvanian known for his protectionist views, as his running mate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, who was personally popular in New England, hoped to assemble a coalition in which Clay attracted Western voters, Rush attracted voters in the middle states, and Webster won over former members of the Federalist Party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams support in New York aligned with the Anti-Masonic Party and Thurlow Weed, his campaign manager in the state, was sympathetic to the anti-masonic movement.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was marked by large amounts of nasty "mudslinging." Jackson's marriage, for example, came in for the vicious attack.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Hammond, in his *Cincinnati Gazette*, asked: "Ought a convicted adulteress and her paramour husband be placed in the highest offices of this free and Christian land?" At the time of the election, Mr. and Mrs.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had been happily, legally married for almost 35 years, but when they met, Rachel had been legally married to Lewis Robards.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the Adams campaign managers' hands, this became a scandal.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Decades later, their youthful love story became a political liability.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson believed that attacks on him were personal vendettas consequent to past disputes, writing, "I am branded with every crime, and Doctor McNary, Col.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Erwin, Anderson and Williams are associated for this purpose." One thing that all these men had in common is that they had all known and/or been business partners and/or been military comrades of Jackson going back decades.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson's campaigners fired back by claiming that while serving as minister to Russia, Adams had procured a young girl to serve as a prostitute for Emperor Alexander I.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They also stated that Adams had a billiard table in the White House and that he had charged the government for it.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (In fact Adams while minister to Russia had employed a young girl as a maid to his wife; the girl had written a letter which had been intercepted by the Russian postal services.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander I had been curious to meet the letter writer publicly at court and Adams had done so.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The billiard table was Adams' personal property; a bill for repairing it had been accidentally included in the White House expense accounts.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams also came under attack for having a chess set).
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson also came under heavy attack as a slave trader who bought and sold slaves and moved them about in defiance of modern standards of morality (he was not attacked for merely owning slaves used in plantation work).
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Coffin Handbills attacked Jackson for his courts-martial, execution of deserters, and massacres of Indian villages, and also his habit of dueling and that he supposedly fought over 100 duels.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, Jackson had only fought three duels: in the first both men had fired at each other but made up; in the second duel, Jackson vs John Sevier, it had taken place but only two persons not connected with either party had been slightly injured.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The third duel was with Charles Dickinson in which Dickinson was mortally wounded while Jackson was left with a bullet in his chest.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] A so-called fourth duel between Jackson and Thomas Hart Benton was in fact a frontier brawl which left Jackson badly wounded in the shoulder.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] That said the list of violent incidents involving Andrew Jackson began with his arrival in Tennessee in the 1780s and continued apace for years.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Ezra Stiles Ely attacked Adams' Unitarian beliefs and called for Christians to vote for Jackson.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson avoided articulating issue positions, instead campaigning on his personal qualities and his opposition to Adams.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams avoided popular campaigning, instead emphasizing his support of specific issues.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's praise of internal improvements in Europe, such as "lighthouses of the skies" (observatories), in his first annual message to Congress, and his suggestion that Congress not be "palsied by the will of our constituents" were given attention in and out of the press.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] People kissed babies, had picnics, and started many other traditions during the campaign.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson wrote of the outcome of the contingent election of 1825 in a letter to William H.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the next election, Jackson's and Adams's supporters saw value in establishing the opinion of Jefferson in regards to their respective candidates and against their opposition.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson died on July 4, 1826, on the same day as his predecessor, John Adams, Adams's father.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Webster recorded that Jefferson told him in December 1824 that Jackson was a dangerous man unfit for the presidency.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Historian Sean Wilentz described Webster's account of the meeting as "not wholly reliable." Biographer Robert V.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Gilmer accused Coles of misrepresentation, in Jefferson's opinion had changed, Gilmer said.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's son-in-law, former Virginia Governor Thomas Mann Randolph Jr., said in 1826 that Jefferson had a "strong repugnance" to Henry Clay.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Others said the same thing, but Coles could not believe Jefferson's opinion had changed.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles released a letter from Jefferson meant to be kept private to Thomas Ritchie's *Richmond Enquirer*.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was written after Adams's first annual message to Congress and it contained an attack from Jefferson on the incumbent administration.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Giles omitted a prior letter of Jefferson's praise of Adams for his role in the embargo of 1808.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson Randolph soon collected and published Jefferson's correspondence.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] 22.2% of the voting age population and 57.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] All of the states, except for Delaware and South Carolina, selected their electors through a popular vote.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The selection of electors began on October 31 with elections in Ohio and Pennsylvania and ended on November 13 with elections in North Carolina.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College met on December 3.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won the same states that his father had won in the election of 1800 (the New England states, New Jersey, and Delaware) and Maryland, but Jackson won all other states and won the election in a landslide.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party in Georgia was hopelessly divided into two factions (Troup and Clark) at the time.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, both factions nominated Jackson for President, with the election being primarily a test of the strength of these two factions - the Adams electors ran a very poor third, with just 3.21% of the vote.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The winning slate, which received a 3,000 vote majority.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson received 50.3% of the vote in states without slavery while he received 72.6% of the vote in states with slavery.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] He received 200,000 votes in the South and 400,000 votes in the North, but the Three-fifths Compromise, which inflated the South's electoral votes, resulted in him receiving 105 electoral votes from the South and 73 votes from the North.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election in American history in which the incumbent president lost re-election despite winning a greater share of the popular vote than in the previous election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Adams' loss was also the second time an elected president lost the popular vote twice, this also occurred with Benjamin Harrison in 1888 and 1892, and Donald Trump who lost the popular vote in 2016 and 2020.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which the Democrats won Kentucky until 1856.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the only election where Maine, New Hampshire, New Jersey, and Vermont voted for the National Republicans, and the last time that New Hampshire voted against the Democrats until 1856.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election in which an electoral vote split occurred in Maine until the election of 2016, the first election in which the winning ticket did not have a north–south balance, and the first election in which two northerners ran against two southerners.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] (b) *Votes cast for Jackson electors nominated by the Clark faction of the Democratic Party of Georgia.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two tickets pledged to Jackson ran in this state; the Clark ticket was defeated by electors nominated by the Troup faction.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] There were two Jackson tickets in Georgia representing different factions of the party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The Troup faction "won" with 9,712 votes and the Clarke faction lost with 7,991.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] They are combined here, though legally this is incorrect.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The state rejected returns from 10 counties and 8 others submitted none.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Including the rejected returns, the total votes are Jackson (Troup) 10,508, Jackson (Clarke) 8,854 and Adams, 642.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In Maryland's 3rd and 4th districts, voters voted for two electors, with each pledged to one candidate or another.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] The votes in the 3rd were 6,177 for William Fitzhugh Jr. and 6,164 for William Tyler, both for Jackson, versus 6,117 for George Baltzell and William Price for Adams.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] In the 4th the votes were 6,058 for Benjamin Chew Howard and James Sewell for Jackson versus 5,743 and 5,742 for the Adams electors.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Note: Dubin mistakenly swapped the 3rd and 4th districts in his book, but that has been corrected here.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Two statewide electors were chosen by the electors elected at the district level.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Rachel Jackson had been having chest pains throughout the campaign, and she was traumatized by the personal attacks on her marriage.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] She became ill and died on December 22, 1828.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson accused the Adams campaign, and Henry Clay even more so, of causing her death, saying, "I can and do forgive all my enemies.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Andrew Jackson was sworn in as president on March 4, 1829.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] After the inauguration, a mob entered the White House to shake the new president's hand, damaging the furniture and lights.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson escaped through the back, and large punch bowls were set up to lure the crowd outside.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] Conservatives were horrified at this event, and held it up as a portent of terrible things to come from the first Democratic president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] When Jackson arrived in Washington, D.C., he was to pay the customary courtesy call on the outgoing president, but he refused to do so.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1828-united-states-presidential-election] John Quincy Adams responded by refusing to go to the inauguration of Andrew Jackson, similar to his father who did not attend the inauguration of Thomas Jefferson 28 years before.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The **1831 National Republican National Convention** was held to determine the presidential ticket of the National Republican Party in the 1832 United States presidential election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The convention was held in Baltimore, Maryland in December 1831.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The party nominated Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky for president and former Representative John Sergeant of Pennsylvania for vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] The 1831 National Republican National Convention was the first U.S. presidential nominating convention held by a major party, though a third party, the Anti-Masonic Party, had held a presidential nominating convention earlier in 1831.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] 155 delegates from 18 of the 24 states attended the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Clay was the unanimous choice for president of the party's delegates.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] He was the first sitting member of the United States Senate to be nominated for president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] In the 1832 presidential election, Clay was defeated by President Andrew Jackson of the Democratic Party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] After the 1832 election, the National Republican Party, the Anti-Masonic Party, and other opponents of Jackson coalesced into the Whig Party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1831-national-republican-national-convention] Thus, the 1831 convention was the only national convention ever held by the National Republican Party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The **1832 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 21 to May 23, 1832, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the first presidential nominating convention ever held by the Democratic Party, incumbent President Andrew Jackson was nominated for a second term, while former Secretary of State Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Anti-Masonic Party and the National Republican Party had held the first presidential nominating conventions in 1831, and Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet" helped organize a Democratic convention in 1832.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] As the party leaders assumed that Jackson would be nominated for president, the primary purpose of the convention was to find a new running mate: Vice President John C.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun had fallen out with Jackson following the Petticoat affair and the Nullification Crisis, and subsequently resigned the office in order to take a Senate seat.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention, which was presided over by Governor Robert Lucas, hosted delegates from every state except Missouri; Jackson won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] With Jackson's strong endorsement, Van Buren easily won the vice presidential nomination on the first ballot, defeating former Representative Philip P.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barbour of Virginia and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Jackson and Van Buren went on to win the 1832 presidential election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] In the summer of 1822, "Richmond Junto" leader Thomas Ritchie of Virginia began raising the idea of a national convention to resolve the issue of nomination; ultimately, the congressional nominating caucus was appealed to by the devotees of Treasury Secretary William H.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Following that defeat in the election of 1824, early in 1827, Van Buren privately made the argument to Richie for an exclusive national convention of Republicans to ensure Jackson's nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] However, it did not immediately come to fruition while state conventions and legislatures took up Jackson as their presidential candidate for the election of 1828 with Vice President John C.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Such a type of national convention would occur after the election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Calhoun soon became politically estranged from President Jackson, due in part to an 1830 letter written by Crawford stating that Calhoun, as Secretary of War under President James Monroe, pushed for a reprimand of then-General Jackson for his actions in the 1818 invasion of Florida.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The Petticoat affair in which Calhoun's wife, Floride, was a central figure further alienated Jackson from the vice president and his supporters.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The final blow to the relationship came in January 1832, when Calhoun, as President of the Senate, sank Van Buren's nomination as Minister to Great Britain by casting a tie-breaking vote in the United States Senate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Calhoun was replaced as the party's 1832 vice presidential nominee by Van Buren.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Later that year, on December 28, he resigned as vice president, after having been elected to the U.S.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] There he continued to be a proponent of the doctrine of nullification in opposition to Jackson.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The proposal for the convention began with members of Jackson's "Kitchen Cabinet", his coterie of informal advisers and confidants.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Major William Berkeley Lewis wrote on May 25, 1831, to Amos Kendall, who was then in New Hampshire.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] He proposed that the New Hampshire legislature call for a national gathering of Republican supporters of the Jackson administration to nominate a candidate for the vice presidency, and asked Kendall to pass the idea to Isaac Hill.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention was called to order by Frederick A.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from all states except Missouri were present.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Governor Robert Lucas of Ohio served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Peter Vivian Daniel, James Fenner, John M.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Barclay, and Augustin Smith Clayton were chosen as convention vice presidents.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] John Adams Dix was appointed secretary at the first meeting, with other additional secretaries thereafter.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] A resolution was passed by the convention requiring two-thirds majority support of the delegates for a nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] An address by the Republican delegates of New York gave a history of previous national political activity in the United States.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] They denounced the National Republicans as Federalists under a new designation and they denounced the Nullifiers while they declared that their own party held the middle ground between the positions of the other two.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The address described what they claimed were political similarities between Andrew Jackson and Thomas Jefferson and it defended the policies of Jackson's administration.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] It characterized Van Buren as a strict constructionist and welcomed his nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] The convention concluded by adopting a resolution calling for an address or report from the delegations to their constituents.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Jackson was nominated via a resolution passed by the convention, affirming the nominations which Jackson had previously received from multiple state legislatures.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Martin Van Buren was nominated for vice president on the first ballot after receiving 208 votes of the 283 cast, 19 more than the two-thirds majority required to win.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1832-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Jackson and Martin Van Buren defeated their main competitors, Henry Clay and John Sergeant of the National Republican Party, by a large electoral vote margin in the election of 1832.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The **1835 Democratic National Convention** was held from May 20 to May 22, 1835, in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The convention nominated incumbent Vice President Martin Van Buren for president and Representative Richard Mentor Johnson of Kentucky for vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Former Speaker of the House Andrew Stevenson served as the convention chairman.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] With the support of President Andrew Jackson, Van Buren won the presidential nomination unanimously.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson narrowly won the two-thirds majority necessary for the vice presidential nomination, overcoming a challenge from William Cabell Rives of Virginia.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket of Van Buren and Johnson went on to win the 1836 presidential election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] On February 23, 1835, President Andrew Jackson wrote to James Gwin of Tennessee and claimed a preference for someone who would "most likely to be the choice of the great body of republicans" in regard to his successor.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] He expressed the desire to hold another national convention to nominate candidates for the presidency and vice presidency.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] He instructed Gwin to show the letter to the editor of the *Nashville Republican*.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The newspaper later reprinted the letter.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Andrew Stevenson of Virginia served as the chairman and convention president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Six convention vice presidents and four secretaries were appointed.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Tennessee, Illinois, South Carolina, and Alabama sent no delegates to the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] President Jackson had long planned for Vice President Martin Van Buren to succeed him, and Van Buren was the unanimous choice of the delegates for the presidency.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Jackson and other major Democrats had settled on Richard Mentor Johnson, a Kentucky representative who had fought in the War of 1812, as Van Buren's running mate, but many Virginia Democrats backed William Cabell Rives, the former Ambassador to France.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] A man from Tennessee, Edward Rucker, who was present at the convention but was not sent as a delegate, cast all 15 votes Tennessee was entitled to for Van Buren, and for Johnson for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was nominated for vice president after winning one vote more than the two-thirds majority required.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The delegation of Virginia declared that it had no confidence in Johnson's character and principles, and would not support him.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Letters went out on May 23 from the convention president and vice presidents asking for the acceptance of the nominations by the nominees.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren replied and accepted the nomination on May 29; Johnson, likewise on June 9.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] The Whigs did not put forward a national ticket nominated by national convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren defeated his many competitors for the presidency in the general election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] While the electors of Virginia supported Van Buren for the presidency, they cast their vice presidential votes for William Smith.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] Consequently, Johnson received a plurality, but not a majority, of the electoral votes for the vice presidency.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1835-democratic-national-convention] In the subsequent contingent election in the Senate, Johnson was elected vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The **1839 Whig National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held from December 4 to December 8 in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] It was the first national convention ever held by the Whig Party, and was organized to select the party's nominee in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The convention nominated former Senator William Henry Harrison of Ohio for president and former Senator John Tyler of Virginia for vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] With Southern delegates united behind him, Clay led on the first presidential ballot, but failed to win a majority.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison won the nomination on the fifth ballot after several delegates switched from supporting Clay or Scott.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The convention chose Tyler, a Southerner and Clay supporter, to serve as Harrison's running mate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] The Whig ticket went on to win the 1840 election, defeating incumbent Democratic President Martin Van Buren.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Clay led on the first ballot, but circumstances conspired to deny him the nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] First, the convention came on the heels of a string of Whig electoral losses, and party members were anxious to reverse the trend.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison managed to distance himself from the losses, but Clay, as the party's philosophical leader, could not.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Had the convention been held in the spring of 1840, when the continuing economic downturn caused by the Panic of 1837 led to a string of Whig victories, Clay would have had much greater support.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Second, the convention rules had been drawn up so that whoever won the majority of delegates from a given state would win all the votes from that state.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Third, several Southern states whose Whig party organizations supported Clay abstained from sending delegates to the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Harrison won on the fifth ballot after Clay delegates from Illinois and Scott delegates from Michigan, New York, and Vermont combined to switch their support to Harrison.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Writer and activist John Neal, who chaired the delegation from Maine, claimed to have been instrumental in convincing the powerful New York delegation to back Harrison prior to the final vote.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Because Harrison (born in Virginia) was considered a Northerner (as a resident of Ohio), the Whigs needed to balance the ticket with a Southerner.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] They also sought a Clay supporter to help unite the party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] After being turned down by several potential candidates, including John J.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Crittenden, John Bell, and Willie Person Mangum, the convention finally found its Southerner who had faithfully supported Clay and would accept: former Senator John Tyler.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Tyler was well known to the delegates, having previously been the running mate of Hugh Lawson White and Willie Person Mangum during the four-way Whig campaign of 1836.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] He was easily nominated on the first ballot.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] During the balloting, Clay and Scott played cards with two Whig politicians, John J.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Crittenden and George Evans, at the Astor House hotel in New York City.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] When the group received word of Harrison's victory, Clay blamed his loss on Scott and punched him, hitting the shoulder which had been wounded during Scott's participation in the Battle of Lundy's Lane, before being physically removed from the hotel room.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1839-whig-national-convention] Scott then sent Crittenden to Clay with Scott's challenge for a duel, but Crittenden reconciled them by convincing Clay to apologize.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Abolitionists held a presidential nominating convention on April 1 and 2, 1840, at the City Hall in Albany, New York, and nominated James G.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney of New York for president and Thomas Earle of Pennsylvania for vice president in the 1840 United States presidential election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Although the name was not in general use at the time, this is considered the founding convention of the Liberty Party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Delegates from six states attended the convention, which was preceded by local abolitionist meetings in the burned-over district of Upstate New York.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] New Yorkers accounted for all but a handful of those present, while the remainder came chiefly from New England.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Winter weather and lack of funds precluded the attendance of delegates from Pennsylvania and the Old Northwest.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Garrisonian abolitionists opposed any involvement in electoral politics and attended with the aim to prevent an independent nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Robust debate between the Garrisonians and the political abolitionists preceded the voting on the second day of the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The motion to nominate candidates for president and vice president narrowly passed, and the convention named Birney and Earle as the national ticket.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention did not specify a name for the new party, and Birney and Earle were known variously as the Abolitionist, Freemen's, Human Rights, Liberty, and People's ticket.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The pair polled 0.3 percent of the vote in the fall election, which was won by the Whig candidate, William Henry Harrison.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Abolitionists debated their stance on electoralism during the 1830s, with a minority favoring creation of a new abolitionist party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Alvan Stewart and Myron Holley emerged as the most prominent political abolitionists.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The need for political action was evident from the failure of existing institutions to respond to moral suasion.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Initially, most abolitionists preferred to work within the established two-party system.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] By 1839, efforts to influence the Democratic and Whig parties had apparently failed.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Adherents to the philosophy of nonresistance opposed participation in the electoral system as a moral and religious principle.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Many abolitionists believed that political parties were essentially corrupt and warned that a descent into partisanship would undermine the movement's moral message.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Interest in an independent abolitionist party increased following the 1839 Whig National Convention in response to the nominations of William Henry Harrison and John Tyler, both slaveholders, as the national Whig candidates.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley travelled across Upstate New York tirelessly advocating for independent nominations in the fall of 1839.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The New York State Anti-Slavery Society held a convention at the Presbyterian church in Warsaw, New York, on November 13 and 14, 1839.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The more than 500 attendees included abolitionists from Western New York and neighboring Pennsylvania.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Josiah Andrews of Perry, New York, presided over the meeting, while Holley and William L.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Chaplin served on the five-member committee on resolutions.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The sixth resolution endorsing the creation of a new abolitionist party was adopted unanimously.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention nominated Birney for president and Francis Julius LeMoyne of Pennsylvania for vice president, and appointed Holley, Andrews, and Joshua H.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Darling to prepare an address to the electorate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Both Birney and LeMoyne declined the nomination of the Warsaw convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne felt an independent ticket was untimely and inexpedient, and warned that the action of the convention suggested a worrying lack of confidence in the moral influence of abolitionism.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney approved the principle of independent nominations, but felt the Warsaw convention was not an appropriate venue, and that a candidate should be selected by a national gathering of abolitionists.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] His conditional refusal set in motion the chain of events that would culminate in the first national convention of the unnamed new abolitionist party the following year.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A gathering of between 600 and 700 abolitionists from the vicinity of Genesee County, New York, met at Arcade, New York, on January 28 and 29, 1840.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley and Gerrit Smith were the principal organizers of this meeting.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Reuben Sleeper was president of the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates met in a temporary structure constructed for the purpose, the village meeting house having been found too small to admit the crowds that flocked from as far away as 60 miles in all directions.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley, Smith, and Chaplin led the political abolitionists on the floor of the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A large number of antislavery Whigs attended in order to oppose the formation of a new abolitionist party, but were outvoted three to one by the advocates of independent nominations.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The resolutions adopted by the convention denounced the Harrison-Tyler ticket and the Democratic incumbent president Martin Van Buren and endorsed the creation of a new abolitionist party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates called for a national convention of the "friends of the immediate abolition of slavery" to meet at Albany on April 1 to nominate candidates for president and vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The action of the Arcade convention elicited a flurry of controversy.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] William Lloyd Garrison denounced the gathering in the pages of *The Liberator* and mocked the attendees as a handful of fringe "malcontents" claiming to speak for the national abolitionist movement.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Phelps defended political abolitionists against charges of inconsistency and moral laxity, responding that the intransigence of the existing parties created a religious obligation for abolitionists to act independently.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Phelps argued that it was the moral character of politicians, not politics, that led to corruption, and that a new party would invite the participation of Christians alienated by the opportunism of the Whigs and Democrats.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Goodell expressed strong reservations against permanent political parties, and called instead for a temporary, single-issue "union" to contest the 1840 election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] James Gillespie Birney was born in 1792 to a slaveholding Kentucky family.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A graduate of Princeton University, he was admitted to the bar and served as a member of both the Kentucky and Alabama legislatures during the 1810s.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He was an early supporter of the American Colonization Society, which advocated for gradual emancipation and the resettlement of free people of color outside the United States.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In 1836, he became a convert to immediatism, manumitted the enslaved people on his Alabama plantation, and relocated to Cincinnati, where he served as the editor of the *Philanthropist* and an officer in the American Anti-Slavery Society (AASS).
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney opposed independent political action by abolitionists as late as 1838, but by 1839 had become one of the most prominent advocates for a new party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He became aligned with the Anti-Garrisonian faction in the AASS and notably broke with Garrison over the equal participation of women in the society's activities, which Garrison supported and Birney opposed.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Following his conditional reply to the Warsaw convention, which stressed the timing and venue of the nominations, he appeared likely to receive the nomination of the Albany convention when it met in April 1840.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney's candidacy was met with reluctance from some political abolitionists, including Leavitt, Wright, and Smith, who preferred a better-known candidate to head the new party's ticket in the fall campaign.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] When it appeared that no other prominent abolitionist would agree to run, some, including Whittier and Henry B.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Stanton, advised postponing the efforts to organize a new party until after the next election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Francis Julius LeMoyne was born in Pennsylvania in 1798.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He graduated from Washington College in 1815 and later attended Jefferson Medical College.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A wealthy physician notable for his diverse intellectual pursuits, LeMoyne was active in the abolitionist movement in his native state, serving as an agent of the Underground Railroad and as president of the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Following the schism of the AASS in May 1840, he served as vice president of the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne opposed the creation of a new party ahead of the 1840 United States elections, which he believed was both premature and dangerously divisive.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He declined the vice presidential nomination of the Warsaw convention when it was offered in November 1839.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In his public reply to the convention, LeMoyne expressed concern that independent nominations would undermine abolitionists' religious message and implied their inability to abolish slavery through moral influence.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Equally seriously, a poor showing in the presidential election would embarrass the abolitionist candidates and expose the movement's internal disunity to public ridicule.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne wrote to Birney that an independent candidacy could permanently alienate Whig and Democratic partisans from the abolitionist movement by forcing them to choose between their antislavery and partisan loyalties.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] LeMoyne's refusal created a vacancy on the ticket that was filled by Thomas Earle, a Hicksite Quaker formerly prominent in the Pennsylvania Abolition Society.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Born in Leicester, Massachusetts, in 1789, Earle attended Leicester Academy.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] He relocated to Philadelphia in 1817, where he practiced law.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Earle was previously a member of the Pennsylvania Democratic Party, from which he was expelled for his abolitionist views.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] His state residence and past partisan connections were the chief reasons for his selection by the Albany convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention met at the Albany City Hall on April 1, 1840.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Of the 121 delegates, 104 came from New York alone; Massachusetts sent the next-largest delegation, with 11 delegates.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Winter weather and insufficient funds prevented the attendance of delegates from outside the Northeastern United States.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Several prominent abolitionists who were unable to be present sent letters to be read to the convention, including Whittier, who advised against independent nominations.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Included among the attendees were several who came with the express purpose of opposing a new abolitionist party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Of the new party advocates, Smith was bedridden and unable to travel to Albany, while Birney, as the prospective candidate, was tactfully absent.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Most of the discussion during the two days of the convention focused on whether to support an independent ticket in the 1840 presidential election, with passionate arguments on both sides.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Beman gave a powerful speech ridiculing the new party movement.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] So persuasive were Beman's arguments that Wright predicted, if the delegates had been polled immediately following his remarks, a majority would have voted against the measure.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley, Leavitt, Stewart, Beriah Green, and Benjamin Shaw (who traveled 90 miles on foot from his Vermont residence to attend the convention) spoke in favor of independent nominations.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Holley spoke immediately after Beman and responded to him directly, arguing for the necessity of a new party; only by independent political action could abolitionists increase their moral influence and demonstrate their consistent opposition to slavery.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Stewart replied that the abolitionists' previous tactics had been ineffective, and only by organizing a new party could they break the hegemony of the Slave Power.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] A vote taken on the evening of the second day resulted in a narrow majority for independent nominations, with 44 votes in favor and 33 against, while more than a third of the delegates abstained.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates then proceeded to nominate Birney and Earle for president and vice president by acclamation.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention deliberately avoided the controversial question of whether to form a permanent organization in order to preserve unity between advocates of a new party and those favoring nonpartisan nominations.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Similarly, eager to recruit as widely as possible, the convention avoided addressing other divisive topics in favor of a narrow emphasis on the abolition of slavery.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The platform was deliberately silent on issues apart from slavery; in the event that Birney and Earle were elected, all other questions would be settled according to the greatest good to all citizens.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] It condemned as "treasonable" the congressional gag rule restricting the introduction of antislavery petitions and endorsed renewed moral and religious efforts to abolish slavery in tandem with political action.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The delegates did not specify a name for the new party, if a party it was.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney and Earle were most frequently called the Abolitionist or Independent Abolitionist ticket, although a variety of other names were used, including the Human Rights Party, the People's Party, the Freemen's Party, and the Liberty Party.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The last was the invention of Gerrit Smith, who used the name as early as February 1840, and was later formally adopted by the 1841 Liberty National Convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention appointed a national committee consisting of Stewart, Smith, and Goodell to coordinate the campaign.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In response to criticism that a gathering dominated by New Yorkers was hardly a "national" convention, the delegates instructed the committee to hold a ratification meeting at New York City in one month's time.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Delegates from 10 of the 13 free states attended the ratification convention at New York City in May 1840, while many abolitionists were in town for the annual meeting of the American Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The meeting was a landmark event in the history of the AASS, which split definitively when opponents of Garrison left to form the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, leaving the Garrisonians in control of the Old Organization.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Across town, the ratification convention confirmed the choice of Birney and Earle as the national ticket, as Birney prepared to set sail for London as part of the American delegation to the World Anti-Slavery Convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The convention received mixed responses from abolitionists.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Garrisonians ridiculed the "April Fools' Convention" as ill-considered and unrepresentative of the national abolitionist movement.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Leavitt, in contrast, gave Birney and Earle his unqualified endorsement and became the independent ticket's most enthusiastic supporter.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Some early skeptics, including Whittier, eventually supported Birney after he formally accepted the nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Bailey finally endorsed Birney before the election, although many of his associates in Ohio supported the Whigs.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Most outsiders took little notice of the nominations or dismissed the ticket as a Democratic ploy to divert abolitionist votes from the national Whig candidates.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Birney remained out of the country until after Election Day and played little part in the campaign.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Few expected the ticket to draw a significant number of votes, least of all Birney himself, who saw his candidacy as a starting point for future efforts.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Electors pledged to Birney and Earle appeared in every free state, where they polled a combined 6,946 votes.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] The ticket put up its strongest performances in Massachusetts and New York, which together accounted for more than half Birney's national total.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] In Connecticut, Indiana, and New Jersey, political abolitionists remained largely unorganized, and Birney polled only a negligible number of votes in these states.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Altogether, Birney and Earle received 0.3 percent of the national popular vote and no electoral votes, finishing a distant third behind Harrison and Van Buren.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-abolitionist-presidential-nominating-convention] Most abolitionists abstained or voted for the larger parties, while only in Massachusetts did Birney poll more than 1 percent of the votes cast.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The **1840 Democratic National Convention** was held in Baltimore, Maryland, from May 5 to May 6.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic Party re-nominated President Martin Van Buren by acclamation, but failed to select a nominee for vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren is the only major party presidential nominee since the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Dragged down by the unpopularity of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was defeated by the Whig Party's ticket in the 1840 presidential election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates from 21 of 26 states were in attendance.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] States not in attendance were Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, South Carolina and Virginia.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The 1840 convention was the first at which the party adopted a platform.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Delegates reaffirmed their belief that the Constitution was the primary guide for each state's political affairs.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] To them, this meant that all roles of the federal government not specifically defined fell to each respective state government, including such responsibilities as debt created by local projects.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Decentralized power and states' rights pervaded each and every resolution adopted at the convention, including those on slavery, taxes, and the possibility of a central bank.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Johnson was not retained on the ticket, as he was largely seen as a liability in the 1836 election and had focused much of his time as vice president on his own economic affairs.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Former president Andrew Jackson backed James K.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk for the position of vice president, but Van Buren supported his vice president's renomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Prior to the convention, several prominent Democrats sought the vice presidential nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Among them were Polk; Senator William R.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] King of Alabama; and Secretary of State John Forsyth of Georgia.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] The convention ultimately failed to nominate a running mate for Van Buren.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Van Buren remains the only major party presidential nominee since the passage of the Twelfth Amendment to seek election without a running mate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/1840-democratic-national-convention] Polk and Johnson would both receive electoral votes for vice president in the general election.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The **2008 Democratic National Convention** was a quadrennial presidential nominating convention of the Democratic Party where it adopted its national platform and officially nominated its candidates for president and vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The convention was held in Denver, Colorado, from August 25 to 28, 2008, at the Pepsi Center.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Barack Obama from Illinois gave his acceptance speech on August 28 at Invesco Field in what the party called an "Open Convention".
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Denver last hosted the Democratic National Convention in 1908.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Obama became the party's first nonwhite nominee, and nominee of African descent, for president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Joe Biden from Delaware was nominated for vice president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Obama officially received the nomination for president on August 27, when his former opponent, U.S.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Hillary Clinton of New York, interrupted the official roll call to move that Obama be selected by acclamation.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Biden accepted the nomination for vice president on the same night.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Obama accepted his nomination the following night in a speech at Invesco Field before a record-setting crowd of 84,000 people in attendance.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Howard Dean presided over the political party in his capacity as Chair of the Democratic National Convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Daughtry served as chief executive of the Democratic National Convention Committee.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Speaker of the House Nancy Pelosi served as permanent chair of the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Sharing in her responsibilities in the convention were three co-chairmen: Kansas Governor Kathleen Sebelius, Texas State Senator Leticia R.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Van de Putte, and Atlanta Mayor Shirley Franklin.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Choosing to hold the convention the day after the Beijing Olympic Games concluded, the Democratic Party convened in Denver in the last week of August, a week before the Republican National Convention in St.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The decision was made, according to the party, to "maximize momentum for our Democratic ticket in the final months of the Presidential election".
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Customarily, the party of the incumbent president holds its convention after the opposing party has held theirs.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic National Committee presented themes for each day of the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The August 26 theme was "Renewing America's Promise" while its August 27 theme was "Securing America's Future".
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The August 28 theme highlights Obama's campaign motto, "Change We Can Believe In".
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Featured speakers crafted their messages to the theme of the day.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] With close delegate counts for Barack Obama and Hillary Clinton, there was early speculation of the first brokered convention in decades.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Democratic National Committee Chair Howard Dean sought to avoid such a circumstance.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In addition to the possibility of a brokered convention, a dispute over seating delegates from Florida and Michigan led some to compare the year's convention with the 1968 Democratic National Convention, which ended in a divided party and unhappiness over the outcome.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] This speculation ended when Obama was declared the presumptive nominee on June 3, 2008, and Clinton officially announced later that week that she was suspending her campaign and was fully endorsing Obama.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] On February 2, 2007, the Democratic Party published "Call for the 2008 Democratic National Convention," the rules governing the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] There were 3,409.5 pledged delegates, those committed to vote for a particular candidate, selected by primary voters and caucus participants.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] There were about 823.5 unpledged delegates, those free to vote for any candidate, colloquially known as "superdelegates", for a total of about 4,233 delegates, requiring 2,117 votes to constitute a majority of the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The superdelegates consisted of DNC members, Democratic Congress members and Governors, and other prominent Democrats.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The pledged delegates were allocated among the states, the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico, according to two main criteria: 1) proportion of votes each state gave the candidate in the last three presidential elections; and 2) percentage of votes each state has in the Electoral College.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Fixed numbers of delegates were allocated for American Samoa, Guam, the United States Virgin Islands, and Democrats Abroad.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Under the party's *Delegate Selection Rules for the 2008 Democratic National Convention*, delegates were awarded through proportional representation with a minimum threshold of 15% of votes in a state or congressional district to receive delegates.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The delegate population must reflect the state's ethnic distribution, and at least 50% of the delegates must be women.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Along with presumptive presidential nominee Barack Obama, former opponent Hillary Clinton's name was also placed in the roll call vote for nomination.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The *Los Angeles Times* noted that this has occurred before: Jerry Brown's name was entered into the roll call after losing to Bill Clinton in 1992; Jesse Jackson and Gary Hart also had their names added after losing to Walter F.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Mondale in 1984; while Jackson's name was also entered into the roll call after losing to Michael Dukakis in 1988.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In 1980, Senator Ted Kennedy's name was entered into the roll call after losing to Jimmy Carter.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In addition, Clinton became only the fourth woman to have her name placed in nomination for president at a major party convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Margaret Chase Smith of Maine was placed in nomination at the 1964 Republican National Convention, and U.S.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Shirley Chisholm of New York was placed in nomination at the 1972 Democratic National Convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In 1976, anti-abortionist Ellen McCormack had her name placed in nomination along with Mo Udall, Jimmy Carter and Jerry Brown.) Clinton would have her name placed in nomination for president once more, in 2016, along with Bernie Sanders.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] All votes cast by the delegates will be counted, and that I move Senator Barack Obama of Illinois be selected by this convention by acclamation as the nominee of the Democratic Party for president of the United States." This was done and the verbal roll call vote was halted.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Earlier the same day, Clinton had released her delegates, allowing them to vote for Obama.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Along with the verbal roll call, a paper ballot was taken.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The results were 3,188.5 for Obama and 1,010.5 for Clinton.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] There are an additional 219 votes that were not cast.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Paul, Nashville, New Orleans, New York City, Orlando, Philadelphia, Phoenix, Pittsburgh, Portland, St.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Louis, Sacramento, Salt Lake City, San Antonio, San Diego, San Francisco, Seattle, and Washington, D.C.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Eleven cities originally accepted the invitation to bid for the convention in January 2006: Anaheim, Dallas, Denver, Detroit, Las Vegas, Minneapolis–St.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Paul, New Orleans, New York City, Orlando, Phoenix, and San Antonio.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] A formal request for proposal was mailed to participating cities on February 27 and the deadline for cities to respond was May 19, 2006.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Only three cities submitted final proposals to host the convention: Denver, Minneapolis-St.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] New Orleans had submitted an initial bid, but on July 12, the city dropped out.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The cities were visited by a 10-member Technical Advisory Committee in June 2006.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] On September 27, the Republicans announced they would have their 2008 convention in St.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Paul, removing it from consideration and leaving only Denver and New York as potential hosts.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Despite hard lobbying by New York party boosters, then-Republican Mayor Michael Bloomberg dealt the campaign a major blow when he announced the city lacked the financial means to support a convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Denver was chosen as the host on January 11, 2007, as Democrats looked to make gains in the "Purple West" states of Colorado, Nevada, and New Mexico.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The work to prepare Pepsi Center for the Democratic National Convention was expected to cost $15 million.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In addition, a 220,000-square-foot (20,000 m2) temporary building to be used by the media was built near Pepsi Center.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Convention organizers, including the Democratic National Convention Committee and the Denver 2008 Convention Host Committee, expected 50,000 attendees, of whom 5,000 were delegates and 15,000 media personnel.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] However, they anticipated 75,000 people coming to watch Obama accept the nomination on Thursday.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The stage erected at Invesco Field for the convention's final evening featured doric columns meant to evoke the White House's neoclassical architecture.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Some critics criticized this design as evoking imperial imagery.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The head of the International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees Local No.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] 7, Jim Taylor, refused to sign a no-strike agreement for the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Pepsi Center normally uses nonunion labor, but used Taylor's union during the convention, and Taylor wanted Pepsi Center to use his union for all events.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] As with past political conventions since 2000, the Democratic National Convention was designated a National Special Security Event (NSSE) by the United States Department of Homeland Security (DHS).
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Denver Police Department doubled in size to 3,000 officers for the DNC, by including other police from 52 neighboring law enforcement agencies.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Police were equipped with riot gear in preparation for unorganized protests.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Throughout the event, a total of 152 arrests were made for offenses related to the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The theme for the day was "One Nation," with Michelle Obama as the "headline prime-time speaker." She was introduced by her brother, Craig Robinson.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Also, Maya Soetoro-Ng spoke briefly on growing up with her older brother Barack Obama, and brought an Asian-American presence to the stage for the first time.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] *The Work to Come: A Tribute to Senator Edward Kennedy*, directed and produced by Mark Herzog and Chris Cowen in association with Ken Burns, was introduced by Kennedy's niece, Caroline Kennedy.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Consistent with the theme of the evening, Former Republican congressman Jim Leach gave his public endorsement of Barack Obama.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] His speech was introduced by Senator Tom Harkin, a fellow Iowan.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Kennedy was not expected to attend the convention due to his illness, but nevertheless made a surprise appearance and speech in the evening.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] A video about former President Jimmy Carter's humanitarian work was also shown, followed by a brief appearance by the president himself.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The theme for the day was "Renewing America's Promise." Senator Barbara Mikulski was one of several elected women Democrats selected to speak that evening.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Senator Hillary Clinton was the headline prime-time speaker.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Ohio Representative Dennis Kucinich, who had also run as a presidential candidate in the 2008 Democratic Party primaries, gave a spirited speech structured around the refrain "Wake up America!" The speech levies trenchant criticism of the perceived abuses of power of the George W.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Bush administration, attacks the corporate control of the American political and economic systems and rallies for a program of universal health coverage, universal higher education, tax reform, trade policy reform, energy regulation, civil liberties and de-militarization.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] At the end of the speech, Kucinich endorses Barack Obama and Joe Biden for president and vice-president.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] His words electrified the audience who began delivering a standing ovation midway through the speech and continued cheering past its closure.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The theme for the day was "Securing America's Future".
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] It featured a speech by Joe Biden, the vice presidential candidate.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Before his speech he was introduced by his oldest son Beau Biden, Delaware's Attorney General.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In that speech Beau talked about how his father would tuck him and his siblings into bed each night after returning home, how he refused invitations to cocktail parties in DC because he did not want to miss his granddaughter (Beau's daughter) Natalie's birthday.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] He remembered the accident that killed his mother and sister and how his father took the Senate oath at his and his brother's bedside.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Several years later his father remarried "their Mom Jill" and their family was rebuilt.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In the end Beau, whose Delaware National Guard unit where he is Captain was to be deployed to Iraq, said that while his father was always there for him, his duties that fall would prevent him from being there for his Dad.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Thus he asked his family and everyone else to be there in November for his father and to be there for Barack Obama and make this country better again.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Other speakers included former president Bill Clinton, 2004 presidential candidate Sen.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] After Joe Biden spoke, his first address as vice presidential nominee, Barack Obama made a surprise appearance praising the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The convention moved to Invesco Field at Mile High, with a DNCC record crowd of more than 84,000 people in attendance.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Speakers included former Vice President Al Gore, Governor of Virginia Tim Kaine, Governor of New Mexico Bill Richardson, Illinois Senator Dick Durbin, and the evening culminated in Barack Obama's acceptance speech.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] More than 38 million people across 10 U.S. cable and broadcast TV networks tuned in to watch.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In his speech, Obama said, "Our government should work for us, not against us.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] It should ensure opportunity, not for just those with the most money and influence, but for every American who is willing to work.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] That's the promise of America, the idea that we are responsible for ourselves, but that we also rise and fall as one nation, the fundamental belief that I am my brother's keeper, I am my sister's keeper.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Florida and Michigan legislatures moved forward their primaries to January 2008, in contravention of party rules and were stripped of their delegates.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Clinton campaign with others initially opposed their seating, stating they acknowledged that the delegates from neither Michigan nor Florida would count.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] However, after winning the Florida and Michigan primaries, Senator Clinton spoke in favor of seating the states' delegates (despite Joe Biden, Barack Obama, Bill Richardson, and John Edwards having removed their names from the Michigan primary ballot).
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] DNC Chair Howard Dean asked Florida and Michigan to submit a new plan for a process to choose the delegates, such as holding primaries again, or let the matter be referred to the Credentials Committee.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In May 2008, the rules committee agreed to let their delegates have half a vote each.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In August 2008, Senator Barack Obama, the party's presumptive nominee, asked the credentials committee to let the two states have full voting rights at the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The credentials committee met on August 24, the day before the convention began, and voted to restore full voting rights to Florida and Michigan.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] From March through July, convention planners were provided subsidized and untaxed fuel from municipal government gas pumps at a price less than retail fuel available to ordinary citizens, reportedly without a signed contract.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] After the practice became public at a meeting with city council members, only convention planners' buses were allowed to refuel at city facilities.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit on behalf of 12 organizations who planned to protest at the Democratic Convention, requesting that the Secret Service and Denver officials release information about procedures concerning protesting times and the Demonstration Zone.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In a June 12 release, a parade route and Demonstration Zone were announced.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Demonstration Zone will be in Parking Lot A of Pepsi Center.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Some groups, including two groups opposing abortion chose to delay filing suit after it was announced that their applications for permits are being processed.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In an amended complaint, the ACLU and interested advocacy groups have filed suit against the Secret Service and the city and county of Denver, questioning the constitutionality of the restrictions.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The lawsuit failed and the ACLU did not appeal.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The official demonstration zone was unused on Monday afternoon, as the convention opened.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The 47,000-square-foot (4,400 m2) fenced area was 700 feet (210 m) from Pepsi Center and delegates could pass from 8 to 200 feet (61 m) from it.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The Denver Police Department claimed the facility was set up to allow those arrested to be processed and released in a more timely manner than they would if they were to be transferred to the Denver County Jail, but faced substantial criticism in mainstream media.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] On August 24, three men were arrested in the Denver, Colorado area on drugs and weapons charges.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Following the arrests of Shawn Robert Adolf, Tharin Robert Gartrell and Nathan Johnson, a possible plot to assassinate Senator Obama surfaced.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Authorities later said they had determined the trio posed no credible danger to Obama; U.S.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] A reporter from ABC News was arrested as he was photographing a meeting of Democratic senators and VIP donors.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The reporter, Asa Eslocker, was arrested by the Denver police and charged with trespassing, interference, and failure to follow a lawful order.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The charges were dismissed by the Denver city attorney.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] On August 26, 2008, a group of anti-abortion activists from American Right to Life Action constructed a sign on Table Mountain outside Denver, overlooking the convention.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The sign, made of 2400 sheets, read "Destroys / uNborn / Children" in three rows; it was lined up so that "DNC" appeared vertically in a different color.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Later that day, the protesters were asked by the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department to remove the sign.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] No citations were issued, though the group did violate two open space regulations of not applying for a special activity permit and going into a restricted and closed area that is considered sensitive to wildlife.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Microsoft was chosen as the web content provider for the convention web site, along with Vertigo Software as the developer.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The video application developed was based on Microsoft's Silverlight platform and provided high-definition video streams.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The choice of technology that required proprietary software from a company with a history of antitrust problems was criticized for both the exclusion of competing platforms by way of Silverlight's proprietary video codec and for requiring visitors to install the software when visiting the site.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Although Moonlight is a cross-platform alternative that attempts to be compatible with Silverlight, as of the time of the convention it did not support features found in version 2 which were required.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] In contrast, the web site for the 2008 Republican National Convention used Adobe Flash streams provided through Ustream.TV and YouTube which are viewable with several applications including the free software cross-platform clone Gnash.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Ava DuVernay was commissioned by the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture to create a film which debuted at the museum's opening on September 24, 2016.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] This film, *August 28: A Day in the Life of a People*, tells of six significant events in African-American history that happened on the same date, August 28.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] The 22-minute film stars Lupita Nyong'o, Don Cheadle, Regina King, David Oyelowo, Angela Bassett, Michael Ealy, Gugu Mbatha-Raw, André Holland and Glynn Turman.
[src:2008-democratic-national-convention/2008-democratic-national-convention] Events depicted include, among other things, the night Obama accepted the Democratic nomination for president at the convention.
